release.description:
Plugin installs an ehcache.xml file that has a distributed cache as well as a local cache that can be used by a service
and a tag lib.  Allows for each environment to have their ip address defined in config.  This allows boxes that have more than
one interface to define which interface should be used with ehcache.

Ubuntu users:
Modify your ${GRAILS_HOME}/bin/grails (exe on windows) to have the following:
export JAVA_OPTS=" $JAVA_OPTS -Djava.rmi.server.hostname=<hostname>"
Based on the ehcache FAQ <http://ehcache.sourceforge.net/documentation/faq.html> this only needs to be done on ubuntu machines

How to monitor the distributed caches ÔøΩ

Modify your ${GRAILS_HOME}/bin/grails (exe on windows) so that the JVM starts with the following params. Note you should only be doing the following in development.

export JAVA_OPTS=" $JAVA_OPTS -Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.port=9004"
export JAVA_OPTS=" $JAVA_OPTS -Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.authenticate=false"
export JAVA_OPTS=" $JAVA_OPTS -Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.ssl=false"

Add the following to your BootStrap.groovy:

class BootStrap {

	def sessionFactory
    def init = {servletContext ->
		CacheManager manager = new CacheManager()

		MBeanServer mbs = ManagementFactory.getPlatformMBeanServer()

		// Define ObjectName of the MBean
		ObjectName on = new ObjectName("Hibernate:type=statistics,application=ApplicationName");

		// Enable Hibernate JMX Statistics
		StatisticsService statsMBean = new StatisticsService();

		statsMBean.setSessionFactory(sessionFactory);
		statsMBean.setStatisticsEnabled(true);
		mbs.registerMBean(statsMBean, on);

		/**
		 * Enable Ehcache JMX Statistics
		 * Use CacheManager.getInstance() instead of new CacheManager()

		 * as net.sf.ehcache.hibernate.SingletonEhCacheProvider is used
		 * to ensure reference to the same CacheManager instance as used
		 * by Hibernate
		 */
		ManagementService.registerMBeans(manager, mbs, true, true, true, true);

	}
	def destroy = {
	}
}

Now start up the application and use jconsole to connect to your local system.

